on foot if you’re a woman! Even if you live on a busy avenue in the capital of Dakar. As a child I remember walking through the city, with my head down or at worst glancing up at the bus banners as our beloved public transport shuttles me around the capital.

Walking is not only a form of exercise for the body, but it can also open the mind. An opportunity to observe little things you wouldn’t notice when staring at your phone. There’s a new study that even suggests that just looking away from your smartphone screens for a few moments each day has the potential to enhance your psychological wellbeing!

Most of us acknowledge the fact that the technology can possess a serious addictive potential for some of us. Other than offering a large number of potential distractions to occupy the mind, our smartphone habits are taking a toll on our mind and body.

What do you think? Well, here’s how smartphones are giving your health a cold shoulder.

It Reduces a Person’s Physical Activity and Social Interaction

Grasping the smartphone for long hours reduces a person’s physical activity and social interaction. People now spent time on mobile phones instead of doing sports, which can negatively affect their health. Furthermore, human-to-human communication has become less likely in modern society, and small talk is a rarity. Positive human interaction also keeps the gut microbiome healthy, giving it a routine that in turn creates the right environment for the body to process nutrition.
